About 1922.

Gift of E. Mc Jenks.

Wall Street and environs, west from Water Street, showing office structures forming the financial district. The skyscraper under construction is the 70 storied Bank of Manhattan at No. 40 Wall Street. To the left is the 35 story Wall and Hanover Building. To the right are, the 26-story building (No. 62-67 Pine Street) at the rear of No. 60 Wall Street (H.L. Dougherty and Company), the domed Singer Building, the massive Equitable Building, the modern No. 1 Cedar Street, the Transportation Building and the ornate Woolworth Building. Note on Wall Street the glimpses of the Bankers Trust Company (pyramidal tower), the Electric Bond and Share Building and the New York Stock Exchange Building. The triangular structures in the left foreground are respectively the 15 storied Beaver Building and the 25 story Munson S.S. Line Building. Obscuring the lower portions of the latter is the 12 story Orient Building.

1929

Ewing Galloway

Wall Street, east from Water Street to the East River, as seen from the Seaman's Bank for Savings (No. 74 Wall Street). Shown at the foot of Wall Street is Pier No. 12, East River, with a vessel alongside.

Water Street (center for fore to midground) south from Wall Street (foreground, not shown) to Coenties Slip as viewed from the Spreckels Bldg. at Wall Street. The two structures in the center and on opposides of this thoroughfare are the Arbuckle and the W.R. Grace and Co. Buildings. To the left of the former is the Seamans' Church Institute silhouetted against Governor's Island in the Upper Bay.

Wall Street, west from Front Street, showing mainly the south side of same. Note the South Ferry division of the Second and Third Aves. Elevated Lines on Pearl Street. At the S.W. corner of that point appears the 25-storied triangular structure of the Munson Steamship Line. Obscuring same is the 12-story Orient Building at the S.E. corner of that point.

November 7, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
